oceedings of the international conference "Theatre Cultures within Globalising Empires: Looking at Early Modern England and Spain", held in 2012 as part of the ERC Advanced Grant Project Early Modern European Drama and the Cultural Net (DramaNet). Implementing the concept of culture as a virtual network, it investigates Early modern European drama and its global dissemination. The 12 articles of the volume - all written by experts in the field teaching in the United Kingdom, the USA, Russia, Switzerland, India and Germany - focus on a selection of English and Spanish dramas from the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. Analysing and comparing motifs, formal parameters as well as plot structures, they discuss the commonalities and differences of Early modern drama in England and Spain.  afunded by European Research Council (ERC)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 4aElisabethanisches Theater. 4aFrühe Neuzeit. 4aSpanisches Drama. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Drama.2bisacsh  aEarly Modern European Drama.  aEnglish Drama.  aSpanish Drama.1 aVentarola, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakrabarti, Gautam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKüpper, Joachim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Jonathan Gil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKüpper, Joachim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPawlita, Leonie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatritzky